<h3 id="self-reflection">Self Reflection</h3>
<p>Research in pedagogy shows that a key part of learning is taking the time to ask yourself questions about your learning. I‚Äôd like to encourage you to take the time to do this kind of reflection, and there will be a number of assignments throughout the course with this goal in mind.</p>
<h3 id="problem-sets">Problem Sets</h3>
<p>There will be a number of ‚ÄúProblem Sets‚Äù during the block. Your job is to solve any 5 of the problems from each set and TeX up solutions to them.</p>
<p>There will be two deadlines for each problem set: a draft deadline, and a final deadline. The draft deadline is optional: you need not submit anything, but you‚Äôll get feedback on anything you do submit. The final deadline is, well, final. The very last problem set will jump directly to a final deadline, for time reasons.</p>
<p>I‚Äôll grade each problem out of 5 points. In order for you to get full credit for a solution, your solution must be ‚Äúthorough,‚Äù in the sense that it must be:</p>
<ul>
<li>Correct.</li>
<li>Complete: every assertion you make should be accompanied with a formal proof (or a reference to a result that‚Äôs proved in the textbook). If your solution makes use of an unproved assertion, it is incomplete, even if that assertion happens to be true.</li>
<li>Written with good ‚Äústyle.‚Äù This is a little vague, but there are many examples of proofs with good ‚Äústyle‚Äù in the textbook. You‚Äôll notice, for example, that most of the proofs in the textbook are mostly written in complete sentences. A proof that is written entirely in symbols, even if correct and complete, is not good ‚Äústyle.‚Äù (An occasional typo or minor grammar issues are fine; this isn‚Äôt an English class!)</li>
</ul>
<p>A word of warning: I‚Äôll likely be a little strict about all of the above points! Remember that training your proof-writing skills is a central goal of this class. When you first start writing proofs, it‚Äôs natural to feel unsure about your proofs. There are several things you can do if you feel unsure:</p>
<ul>
<li>Submit something by the draft deadline so you get my feedback.</li>
<li>Ask me, Elizabeth, or Cinea for help.</li>
<li>Get a classmate to read your proof and have them point out anything they don‚Äôt understand.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you submit more than 5 solutions, I will start by grading the first 5 that show up in your TeX document. If those 5 are all thorough, you‚Äôll get 1 point of extra credit for each additional thorough solution that shows up after that. If any of your first 5 solutions aren‚Äôt thorough, the later solutions won‚Äôt count for anything. I want you to feel confident about your solutions!</p>
<p>You are welcome to order solutions in your document in any order (eg, descending order of how confident you are about them), but please make sure to number problems as they are numbered on the problem sets and to ‚Äú<a href="https://help.gradescope.com/article/ccbpppziu9-student-submit-work#submitting_a_pdf">assign pages</a>‚Äù correctly on Gradescope.</p>
<p>Finally, a word about the Honor Code. You‚Äôre allowed to get help on the problem sets from me, Elizabeth, Cinea, and your classmates. But, in the end, your solution must be written up in your own words. If your solution is overly similar to something else (another student‚Äôs solution, something on the internet, etc), it will be reported to the Honor Council.</p>
<h3 id="whats-tex">What‚Äôs TeX?</h3>
<p>First of all, the name: the word ‚ÄúLaTeX‚Äù is pronounced either ‚ÄúLAY-tek‚Äù or ‚ÄúLAH-tek‚Äù, with <em>k</em> sound at the end (not a <em>ks</em> sound). Sometimes people just say TeX (‚Äútek‚Äù) for short.</p>
<p>Next, what it is: LaTeX is a software system for preparing PDF documents. You input the content of your document alongside a little bit of ‚Äúcode,‚Äù all in plaintext, and then you hit compile and out pops a beautifully formatted PDF. Because there‚Äôs a little bit of ‚Äúcode‚Äù involved, there‚Äôs a little bit of a learning curve. But it‚Äôs not too steep, and once you get used to it you‚Äôll find that it‚Äôs by far the most convenient way out there for typesetting mathematical expressions.</p>
<p>People working in mathematically heavy fields TeX up documents all the time, so I think it‚Äôs a useful skill to have. To this end, your PDF submissions for your problem sets are required to be TeXed.</p>
<p>You can either install LaTeX on your computer, or you can use <a href="https://www.overleaf.com">Overleaf</a>. If you haven‚Äôt used LaTeX before, I encourage you to check out Overleaf‚Äôs guide, ‚Äú<a href="https://www.overleaf.com/learn/latex/Learn_LaTeX_in_30_minutes">Learn LaTeX in 30 minutes</a>.‚Äù</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs a <a href="template.tex">template</a> for your problem sets, if you want something to get started. You‚Äôre more than welcome to set up a document yourself.</p>
